1
0:00:13.391,000 --> 0:00:15,000
You probably don't know me,

2
0:00:15.67,000 --> 0:00:18,000
but I am one of those .01 percenters

3
0:00:19.014,000 --> 0:00:2,000
that you hear about and read about,

4
0:00:20.957,000 --> 0:00:24,000
and I am by any reasonable definition a plutocrat.

5
0:00:25.022,000 --> 0:00:28,000
And tonight, what I would like to do is speak directly

6
0:00:28.112,000 --> 0:00:3,000
to other plutocrats, to my people,

7
0:00:30.418,000 --> 0:00:32,000
because it feels like it's time for us all

8
0:00:33.229,000 --> 0:00:35,000
to have a chat.

9
0:00:35.305,000 --> 0:00:37,000
Like most plutocrats, I too am a proud

10
0:00:37.883,000 --> 0:00:39,000
and unapologetic capitalist.

11
0:00:40.226,000 --> 0:00:43,000
I have founded, cofounded or funded

12
0:00:43.763,000 --> 0:00:46,000
over 30 companies across a range of industries.

13
0:00:47.293,000 --> 0:00:5,000
I was the first non-family investor in Amazon.com.

14
0:00:50.888,000 --> 0:00:52,000
I cofounded a company called aQuantive

15
0:00:53.609,000 --> 0:00:56,000
that we sold to Microsoft for 6.4 billion dollars.

16
0:00:57.479,000 --> 0:00:59,000
My friends and I, we own a bank.

17
0:01:00.027,000 --> 0:01:02,000
I tell you this — (Laughter) —

18
0:01:02.923,000 --> 0:01:03,000
unbelievable, right?

19
0:01:04.17,000 --> 0:01:07,000
I tell you this to show

20
0:01:07.38,000 --> 0:01:09,000
that my life is like most plutocrats.

21
0:01:10.143,000 --> 0:01:13,000
I have a broad perspective on capitalism

22
0:01:13.45,000 --> 0:01:14,000
and business,

23
0:01:15.25,000 --> 0:01:18,000
and I have been rewarded obscenely for that

24
0:01:19.04,000 --> 0:01:21,000
with a life that most of you all

25
0:01:21.197,000 --> 0:01:23,000
can't even imagine:

26
0:01:23.456,000 --> 0:01:25,000
multiple homes, a yacht, my own plane,

27
0:01:26.157,000 --> 0:01:3,000
etc., etc., etc.

28
0:01:30.284,000 --> 0:01:33,000
But let's be honest: I am not the smartest person you've ever met.

29
0:01:33.546,000 --> 0:01:35,000
I am certainly not the hardest working.

30
0:01:35.95,000 --> 0:01:36,000
I was a mediocre student.

31
0:01:37.923,000 --> 0:01:38,000
I'm not technical at all.

32
0:01:39.141,000 --> 0:01:41,000
I can't write a word of code.

33
0:01:41.639,000 --> 0:01:44,000
Truly, my success is the consequence

34
0:01:44.772,000 --> 0:01:46,000
of spectacular luck,

35
0:01:47.22,000 --> 0:01:51,000
of birth, of circumstance and of timing.

36
0:01:52.124,000 --> 0:01:56,000
But I am actually pretty good at a couple of things.

37
0:01:56.619,000 --> 0:02:,000
One, I have an unusually high tolerance for risk,

38
0:02:01.263,000 --> 0:02:03,000
and the other is I have a good sense,

39
0:02:03.678,000 --> 0:02:05,000
a good intuition about what will happen in the future,

40
0:02:06.303,000 --> 0:02:09,000
and I think that that intuition about the future

41
0:02:09.586,000 --> 0:02:12,000
is the essence of good entrepreneurship.

42
0:02:13.156,000 --> 0:02:15,000
So what do I see in our future today,

43
0:02:15.674,000 --> 0:02:17,000
you ask?

44
0:02:17.676,000 --> 0:02:18,000
I see pitchforks,

45
0:02:19.331,000 --> 0:02:23,000
as in angry mobs with pitchforks,

46
0:02:24.121,000 --> 0:02:29,000
because while people like us plutocrats

47
0:02:29.335,000 --> 0:02:32,000
are living beyond the dreams of avarice,

48
0:02:32.866,000 --> 0:02:34,000
the other 99 percent of our fellow citizens

49
0:02:35.779,000 --> 0:02:37,000
are falling farther and farther behind.

50
0:02:38.592,000 --> 0:02:4,000
In 1980, the top one percent of Americans

51
0:02:41.08,000 --> 0:02:43,000
shared about eight percent of national [income],

52
0:02:43.558,000 --> 0:02:45,000
while the bottom 50 percent of Americans

53
0:02:46.232,000 --> 0:02:48,000
shared 18 percent.

54
0:02:48.775,000 --> 0:02:51,000
Thirty years later, today, the top one percent

55
0:02:52.127,000 --> 0:02:55,000
shares over 20 percent of national [income],

56
0:02:55.749,000 --> 0:02:56,000
while the bottom 50 percent of Americans

57
0:02:57.65,000 --> 0:02:59,000
share 12 or 13.

58
0:03:00.564,000 --> 0:03:02,000
If the trend continues,

59
0:03:03.01,000 --> 0:03:04,000
the top one percent will share

60
0:03:04.49,000 --> 0:03:06,000
over 30 percent of national [income]

61
0:03:06.796,000 --> 0:03:07,000
in another 30 years,

62
0:03:08.588,000 --> 0:03:1,000
while the bottom 50 percent of Americans

63
0:03:10.868,000 --> 0:03:11,000
will share just six.

64
0:03:12.607,000 --> 0:03:13,000
You see, the problem isn't that we have

65
0:03:14.603,000 --> 0:03:16,000
some inequality.

66
0:03:16.684,000 --> 0:03:18,000
Some inequality is necessary

67
0:03:19.136,000 --> 0:03:22,000
for a high-functioning capitalist democracy.

68
0:03:22.43,000 --> 0:03:23,000
The problem is that inequality

69
0:03:24.14,000 --> 0:03:27,000
is at historic highs today

70
0:03:27.502,000 --> 0:03:3,000
and it's getting worse every day.

71
0:03:30.921,000 --> 0:03:32,000
And if wealth, power, and income

72
0:03:33.545,000 --> 0:03:34,000
continue to concentrate

73
0:03:35.38,000 --> 0:03:37,000
at the very tippy top,

74
0:03:37.681,000 --> 0:03:38,000
our society will change

75
0:03:39.529,000 --> 0:03:4,000
from a capitalist democracy

76
0:03:41.262,000 --> 0:03:44,000
to a neo-feudalist rentier society

77
0:03:45.034,000 --> 0:03:46,000
like 18th-century France.

78
0:03:47.019,000 --> 0:03:5,000
That was France

79
0:03:50.213,000 --> 0:03:51,000
before the revolution

80
0:03:51.96,000 --> 0:03:53,000
and the mobs with the pitchforks.

81
0:03:53.984,000 --> 0:03:55,000
So I have a message for my fellow plutocrats

82
0:03:56.538,000 --> 0:03:57,000
and zillionaires

83
0:03:58.36,000 --> 0:03:59,000
and for anyone who lives

84
0:03:59.834,000 --> 0:04:01,000
in a gated bubble world:

85
0:04:02.07,000 --> 0:04:03,000
Wake up.

86
0:04:03.421,000 --> 0:04:06,000
Wake up. It cannot last.

87
0:04:07.141,000 --> 0:04:09,000
Because if we do not do something

88
0:04:09.16,000 --> 0:04:13,000
to fix the glaring economic inequities in our society,

89
0:04:13.491,000 --> 0:04:15,000
the pitchforks will come for us,

90
0:04:16.236,000 --> 0:04:19,000
for no free and open society can long sustain

91
0:04:20.184,000 --> 0:04:23,000
this kind of rising economic inequality.

92
0:04:23.188,000 --> 0:04:25,000
It has never happened. There are no examples.

93
0:04:26.11,000 --> 0:04:27,000
You show me a highly unequal society,

94
0:04:27.969,000 --> 0:04:28,000
and I will show you a police state

95
0:04:29.448,000 --> 0:04:3,000
or an uprising.

96
0:04:31.215,000 --> 0:04:33,000
The pitchforks will come for us

97
0:04:33.358,000 --> 0:04:34,000
if we do not address this.

98
0:04:35.269,000 --> 0:04:38,000
It's not a matter of if, it's when.

99
0:04:39.117,000 --> 0:04:42,000
And it will be terrible when they come

100
0:04:42.75,000 --> 0:04:43,000
for everyone,

101
0:04:44.201,000 --> 0:04:48,000
but particularly for people like us plutocrats.

102
0:04:49.185,000 --> 0:04:52,000
I know I must sound like some liberal do-gooder.

103
0:04:52.605,000 --> 0:04:54,000
I'm not. I'm not making a moral argument

104
0:04:54.855,000 --> 0:04:57,000
that economic inequality is wrong.

105
0:04:58.117,000 --> 0:05:02,000
What I am arguing is that rising economic inequality

106
0:05:02.403,000 --> 0:05:05,000
is stupid and ultimately self-defeating.

107
0:05:05.924,000 --> 0:05:08,000
Rising inequality doesn't just increase our risks

108
0:05:09.152,000 --> 0:05:1,000
from pitchforks,

109
0:05:11.02,000 --> 0:05:15,000
but it's also terrible for business too.

110
0:05:15.587,000 --> 0:05:18,000
So the model for us rich guys should be Henry Ford.

111
0:05:19.457,000 --> 0:05:22,000
When Ford famously introduced the $5 day,

112
0:05:23.27,000 --> 0:05:25,000
which was twice the prevailing wage at the time,

113
0:05:26.217,000 --> 0:05:28,000
he didn't just increase the productivity

114
0:05:28.287,000 --> 0:05:29,000
of his factories,

115
0:05:30.256,000 --> 0:05:33,000
he converted exploited autoworkers who were poor

116
0:05:33.653,000 --> 0:05:35,000
into a thriving middle class who could now afford

117
0:05:36.353,000 --> 0:05:39,000
to buy the products that they made.

118
0:05:39.57,000 --> 0:05:43,000
Ford intuited what we now know is true,

119
0:05:43.86,000 --> 0:05:47,000
that an economy is best understood as an ecosystem

120
0:05:47.861,000 --> 0:05:48,000
and characterized by the same kinds

121
0:05:49.78,000 --> 0:05:51,000
of feedback loops you find

122
0:05:52.34,000 --> 0:05:53,000
in a natural ecosystem,

123
0:05:54.08,000 --> 0:05:57,000
a feedback loop between customers and businesses.

124
0:05:58.018,000 --> 0:06:01,000
Raising wages increases demand,

125
0:06:01.124,000 --> 0:06:03,000
which increases hiring,

126
0:06:03.205,000 --> 0:06:05,000
which in turn increases wages

127
0:06:05.286,000 --> 0:06:07,000
and demand and profits,

128
0:06:07.916,000 --> 0:06:11,000
and that virtuous cycle of increasing prosperity

129
0:06:12.76,000 --> 0:06:14,000
is precisely what is missing

130
0:06:14.909,000 --> 0:06:18,000
from today's economic recovery.

131
0:06:19.904,000 --> 0:06:23,000
And this is why we need to put behind us

132
0:06:24.522,000 --> 0:06:27,000
the trickle-down policies that so dominate

133
0:06:28.23,000 --> 0:06:29,000
both political parties

134
0:06:30.027,000 --> 0:06:33,000
and embrace something I call middle-out economics.

135
0:06:33.432,000 --> 0:06:35,000
Middle-out economics rejects

136
0:06:35.967,000 --> 0:06:37,000
the neoclassical economic idea

137
0:06:38.284,000 --> 0:06:42,000
that economies are efficient, linear, mechanistic,

138
0:06:42.481,000 --> 0:06:45,000
that they tend towards equilibrium and fairness,

139
0:06:45.608,000 --> 0:06:48,000
and instead embraces the 21st-century idea

140
0:06:49.046,000 --> 0:06:52,000
that economies are complex, adaptive,

141
0:06:52.82,000 --> 0:06:54,000
ecosystemic,

142
0:06:54.822,000 --> 0:06:57,000
that they tend away from equilibrium and toward inequality,

143
0:06:58.17,000 --> 0:06:59,000
that they're not efficient at all

144
0:06:59.92,000 --> 0:07:02,000
but are effective if well managed.

145
0:07:03.205,000 --> 0:07:06,000
This 21st-century perspective

146
0:07:06.476,000 --> 0:07:08,000
allows you to clearly see that capitalism

147
0:07:09.14,000 --> 0:07:12,000
does not work by [efficiently] allocating

148
0:07:12.427,000 --> 0:07:14,000
existing resources.

149
0:07:14.867,000 --> 0:07:19,000
It works by [efficiently] creating new solutions

150
0:07:20.865,000 --> 0:07:21,000
to human problems.

151
0:07:22.12,000 --> 0:07:24,000
The genius of capitalism

152
0:07:24.329,000 --> 0:07:28,000
is that it is an evolutionary solution-finding system.

153
0:07:29.211,000 --> 0:07:34,000
It rewards people for solving other people's problems.

154
0:07:35.162,000 --> 0:07:37,000
The difference between a poor society

155
0:07:38.109,000 --> 0:07:4,000
and a rich society, obviously,

156
0:07:40.426,000 --> 0:07:42,000
is the degree to which that society

157
0:07:43.364,000 --> 0:07:44,000
has generated solutions in the form

158
0:07:45.297,000 --> 0:07:47,000
of products for its citizens.

159
0:07:48.156,000 --> 0:07:49,000
The sum of the solutions

160
0:07:49.977,000 --> 0:07:5,000
that we have in our society

161
0:07:51.968,000 --> 0:07:53,000
really is our prosperity, and this explains

162
0:07:54.342,000 --> 0:07:56,000
why companies like Google and Amazon

163
0:07:56.625,000 --> 0:07:58,000
and Microsoft and Apple

164
0:07:58.988,000 --> 0:08:,000
and the entrepreneurs who created those companies

165
0:08:01.89,000 --> 0:08:04,000
have contributed so much

166
0:08:05.45,000 --> 0:08:07,000
to our nation's prosperity.

167
0:08:08.156,000 --> 0:08:1,000
This 21st-century perspective

168
0:08:10.956,000 --> 0:08:12,000
also makes clear

169
0:08:13.545,000 --> 0:08:15,000
that what we think of as economic growth

170
0:08:15.99,000 --> 0:08:16,000
is best understood as

171
0:08:17.937,000 --> 0:08:19,000
the rate at which we solve problems.

172
0:08:20.431,000 --> 0:08:23,000
But that rate is totally dependent upon

173
0:08:23.849,000 --> 0:08:26,000
how many problem solvers —

174
0:08:27.426,000 --> 0:08:29,000
diverse, able problem solvers — we have,

175
0:08:29.912,000 --> 0:08:31,000
and thus how many of our fellow citizens

176
0:08:32.645,000 --> 0:08:34,000
actively participate,

177
0:08:34.87,000 --> 0:08:37,000
both as entrepreneurs who can offer solutions,

178
0:08:38.52,000 --> 0:08:41,000
and as customers who consume them.

179
0:08:42.162,000 --> 0:08:46,000
But this maximizing participation thing

180
0:08:46.28,000 --> 0:08:47,000
doesn't happen by accident.

181
0:08:47.899,000 --> 0:08:48,000
It doesn't happen by itself.

182
0:08:49.868,000 --> 0:08:52,000
It requires effort and investment,

183
0:08:53.597,000 --> 0:08:55,000
which is why all

184
0:08:56.027,000 --> 0:08:59,000
highly prosperous capitalist democracies

185
0:08:59.258,000 --> 0:09:01,000
are characterized by massive investments

186
0:09:01.807,000 --> 0:09:03,000
in the middle class and the infrastructure

187
0:09:04.372,000 --> 0:09:06,000
that they depend on.

188
0:09:07.24,000 --> 0:09:08,000
We plutocrats need to get this

189
0:09:09.239,000 --> 0:09:12,000
trickle-down economics thing behind us,

190
0:09:12.378,000 --> 0:09:13,000
this idea that the better we do,

191
0:09:14.284,000 --> 0:09:16,000
the better everyone else will do.

192
0:09:16.951,000 --> 0:09:19,000
It's not true. How could it be?

193
0:09:20.871,000 --> 0:09:24,000
I earn 1,000 times the median wage,

194
0:09:24.999,000 --> 0:09:26,000
but I do not buy 1,000 times as much stuff,

195
0:09:27.924,000 --> 0:09:28,000
do I?

196
0:09:28.988,000 --> 0:09:31,000
I actually bought two pairs of these pants,

197
0:09:32.176,000 --> 0:09:33,000
what my partner Mike calls

198
0:09:34.11,000 --> 0:09:35,000
my manager pants.

199
0:09:35.625,000 --> 0:09:37,000
I could have bought 2,000 pairs,

200
0:09:38.561,000 --> 0:09:41,000
but what would I do with them? (Laughter)

201
0:09:41.627,000 --> 0:09:44,000
How many haircuts can I get?

202
0:09:44.656,000 --> 0:09:47,000
How often can I go out to dinner?

203
0:09:48.361,000 --> 0:09:52,000
No matter how wealthy a few plutocrats get,

204
0:09:52.434,000 --> 0:09:55,000
we can never drive a great national economy.

205
0:09:55.978,000 --> 0:10:,000
Only a thriving middle class can do that.

206
0:10:01.671,000 --> 0:10:02,000
There's nothing to be done,

207
0:10:03.368,000 --> 0:10:07,000
my plutocrat friends might say.

208
0:10:07.509,000 --> 0:10:1,000
Henry Ford was in a different time.

209
0:10:10.713,000 --> 0:10:12,000
Maybe we can't do some things.

210
0:10:12.987,000 --> 0:10:14,000
Maybe we can do some things.

211
